{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13865"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13865"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.03,0.11,0.15,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32822"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"560"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic for a routine skin check. During the examination, a lump is found behind his left ear. On questioning, the patient reports that the lump has been present for two years and has been slowly growing during this time. He has no pain or other symptoms associated with the lump. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a current smoker with a 30 pack-year history. He has not had any recent infections. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 2 cm soft, mobile, non-tender subcutaneous mass behind his left ear. The rest of the skin examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lipoma","Neurofibroma","Sebaceous cyst","Enlarged lymph node","Branchial cleft cyst"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical description is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a benign soft tissue tumour composed of mature fat cells. Lipomas typically present as slow-growing, painless, mobile subcutaneous masses. They are usually asymptomatic and can occur anywhere on the body, including behind the ear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurofibroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign nerve sheath tumour that can occur in the skin. While it can be soft and mobile, it is typically associated with caf\u00e9-au-lait spots and other features of neurofibromatosis, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esebaceous cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is also a benign subcutaneous lesion, but it typically has a central punctum and may become inflamed or infected. It is usually firmer than a lipoma and is not as mobile within the subcutaneous tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eenlarged lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be firmer and less mobile than the described lesion. Lymph nodes are also more likely to change in size rapidly in response to infection or inflammation, rather than showing slow growth over two years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebranchial cleft cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital anomaly that typically presents as a painless neck mass. While it can occur near the ear, it is usually located along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle and is often associated with a sinus tract or fistula. The slow growth and location behind the ear in this case make a lipoma more likely than a branchial cleft cyst.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lipomas are benign soft tissue tumours that typically present as slow-growing, painless, mobile subcutaneous masses.","Lipomas can be diagnosed clinically based on their characteristic features, including slow growth, mobility, and soft consistency."],"references":["Haynes J, Arnold K, Aguirre-Oskins C, Chandra S. Evaluation of neck masses in adults. American Family Physcician. 2015;91(10):698-706. Available online: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2015/0515/p698.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32822"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13865"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20808"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20808"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NKAjGxw7RbhrnKnQdHbqwTC2SEQQUW.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NKAjGxw7RbhrnKnQdHbqwTC2SEQQUW.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32822"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-04T08:39:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T14:49:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"ite